==============================================================
MODIFIED FRIEDMANN EQUATIONS DIRECTLY FROM THE ACTION
Curvature–memory cosmology from the b T M^2 theory
==============================================================

Start from the covariant action

    S = ∫ d^4x √(-g) [
            R/(16πG)
          - 1/2 g^{μν} ∂_μ M ∂_ν M
          - a M^4 / 4
          + b T M^2
          + L_b
        ].

For pressureless matter (dust),

    T = -ρ_b.

We consider a spatially flat FRW metric

    ds^2 = -dt^2 + A(t)^2 δ_{ij} dx^i dx^j

with Hubble rate

    H = Ȧ / A,

and homogeneous scalar

    M = M(t).


--------------------------------------------------------------
1. HOMOGENEOUS SCALAR EQUATION
--------------------------------------------------------------

Varying the action with respect to M gives

    □M + a M^3 - 2 b T M = 0.

For dust, T = -ρ_b, so

    □M + a M^3 + 2 b ρ_b M = 0.

In FRW,

    □M = M̈ + 3H Ṁ,

hence the homogeneous field equation is

    M̈ + 3H Ṁ + a M^3 + 2 b ρ_b M = 0.


--------------------------------------------------------------
2. EFFECTIVE ENERGY DENSITY AND PRESSURE
--------------------------------------------------------------

For a homogeneous field, the scalar-sector energy density and pressure are

    ρ_M = 1/2 Ṁ^2 + a M^4/4 - b T M^2

    p_M = 1/2 Ṁ^2 - a M^4/4 + b T M^2.

For dust, T = -ρ_b, so

    ρ_M = 1/2 Ṁ^2 + a M^4/4 + b ρ_b M^2

    p_M = 1/2 Ṁ^2 - a M^4/4 - b ρ_b M^2.

Thus the interaction contributes directly to the background energy
budget.


--------------------------------------------------------------
3. FRIEDMANN EQUATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------

The Einstein equations give

    3H^2 = 8πG ( ρ_b + ρ_M )

    2Ḣ + 3H^2 = -8πG ( p_b + p_M ).

For dust, p_b = 0. Therefore

    3H^2
      = 8πG [ ρ_b + 1/2 Ṁ^2 + a M^4/4 + b ρ_b M^2 ]

and

    2Ḣ + 3H^2
      = -8πG [ 1/2 Ṁ^2 - a M^4/4 - b ρ_b M^2 ].

Equivalently,

    H^2
      = (8πG/3)
        [ ρ_b (1 + b M^2) + 1/2 Ṁ^2 + a M^4/4 ].

This is the modified Friedmann equation directly from the action.


--------------------------------------------------------------
4. EFFECTIVE MATTER ACTIVATION
--------------------------------------------------------------

The matter density appears multiplied by

    1 + b M^2.

So the action-derived theory naturally gives an effective matter coupling

    ρ_b  →  ρ_b^eff = ρ_b (1 + b M^2).

This is the direct analog of the phenomenological activation factor g(z).

Hence the background theory predicts

    g_eff(z) = 1 + b M(z)^2.

This is the key bridge.

The phenomenological activation law

    H^2 = H0^2 [ Ω_m (1+z)^3 g(z) + ... ]

is therefore recovered if

    g(z) = 1 + b M(z)^2.

So the activation factor is not fundamental; it is the square of the
background memory field.


--------------------------------------------------------------
5. RELATION TO THE ACTIVATION COSMOLOGY
--------------------------------------------------------------

In the phenomenological activation model, the effective matter term was

    Ω_m (1+z)^3 g(z).

In the action-derived model, the corresponding term is

    Ω_m (1+z)^3 [1 + b M(z)^2].

Therefore

    g(z) ↔ 1 + b M(z)^2.

This means the phenomenological activation function can be interpreted
as an effective reconstruction of the background memory field.


--------------------------------------------------------------
6. SIGN OF b AND COSMOLOGICAL BEHAVIOUR
--------------------------------------------------------------

For the viable branch

    b < 0,

the factor

    1 + b M^2 = 1 - |b| M^2

reduces the effective matter contribution.

So late-time weakening of the matter sector happens automatically if
the background field grows away from zero or remains non-negligible.

That is exactly the direction needed to mimic dark-energy-like
acceleration without inserting a separate ad hoc activation law.


--------------------------------------------------------------
7. MATTER-SUPPORTED MINIMUM INSERTED INTO THE BACKGROUND
--------------------------------------------------------------

On the b < 0 branch, the matter-supported minimum is

    M_*^2 = 2 |b| ρ_b / a.

Substitute this into

    g_eff = 1 + b M^2 = 1 - |b| M^2.

Then

    g_eff
      = 1 - |b| (2 |b| ρ_b / a)
      = 1 - 2 |b|^2 ρ_b / a.

So on the minimum branch the effective matter coupling becomes

    ρ_b^eff = ρ_b [ 1 - 2 |b|^2 ρ_b / a ].

Thus the matter sector self-suppresses at high enough density through
the memory field.

This is a direct action-level origin for matter activation/suppression.


--------------------------------------------------------------
8. LEADING MODIFIED FRIEDMANN FORM
--------------------------------------------------------------

Keeping only the dominant background terms, the modified Friedmann
equation becomes

    H^2
      = (8πG/3)
        [ ρ_b (1 + b M^2) + 1/2 Ṁ^2 + a M^4/4 ].

In terms of redshift,

    ρ_b(z) = ρ_b0 (1+z)^3

so

    H^2(z)
      = (8πG/3)
        [ ρ_b0 (1+z)^3 (1 + b M(z)^2)
          + 1/2 Ṁ(z)^2
          + a M(z)^4/4 ].

This is the full action-derived background equation.


--------------------------------------------------------------
9. COMPARISON WITH THE PHENOMENOLOGICAL ACTIVATION MODEL
--------------------------------------------------------------

Earlier, the phenomenological model had

    H^2(z) = H0^2 [ Ω_m (1+z)^3 g(z) + (1 - Ω_m) ].

The action-derived theory instead gives

    H^2(z) = H0^2 [
        Ω_m (1+z)^3 (1 + b M(z)^2)
        + Ω_M,kin(z)
        + Ω_M,pot(z)
    ].

So the phenomenological activation function g(z) is replaced by

    1 + b M(z)^2,

and the scalar also contributes explicit kinetic and quartic-potential
terms.

Therefore the action-derived theory is richer than the activation fit:
it contains both

    • effective matter activation/suppression
    • an independent scalar background energy component.


